Everyone beat me to posting what I was thinking. 1. This isn't a privacy matter and she better get a better lawyer.2. This definitely seems to be a copyright matter along with impersonation. Submitting her material without her permission and using her name. I imagine several laws have been broken there.3. The principal clearly should not have his contract renewed because he just violated some very important ethics of his position. However, being a small town he will likely get rewarded instead.4. For all of you wondering about the gunman. Let me tell you how small towns work since I live in one. You literally have about 5-20 people that run the entire town. The police do nothing that they don't want them too. They will not want to have the police do much investigation because either one of their relatives performed the shooting or one of the police officers did. They will close the books on it as quickly as they can. The town willingly goes along with this because "the family clearly got what they deserved".
TheException
Wise, Aged Ars Veteran
Registered: Feb 13, 2009Posts: 130
Posted: Thu Apr 09, 2009 7:36 am
For starters, I agree that this is screwed up in a lot of ways. However, there's still plenty of blame to go around in favor of this girl. For starters, the principal had no right to republish, especially submitting it to a newspaper under a false name (even if Moreno was the author, she didn't submit the story, nor would she have, it seems). Secondly, while they're both "public", and as a matter of legality probably indistinguishable, it's worth noting that the readership of a local newspaper and the readership of a college students MySpace blog are two entirely different things. Anything I post here, I rarely expect is going to be seen by a massive number of farmers, or florists. (Nature is the opposite of technology, after all.....Wait...) This doesn't mean I don't watch what I say, or be respectful, but it also doesn't mean that I'm broadcasting "to the whole world". Possible access is not the same as practical access.But most of all, the principal, as well as apparently many others in this town, are dicks. The girl wrote what she thought on a MySpace blog. These people are making death threats. I can't believe I'm saying it, but I think that the complaining college student is actually the more mature one in this scenario.Side Note to dlux: You'll forgive me for playing moron's advocate, but I don't think that being "anti-religious" in the context of free speech is the same as being atheist. In a world where this law professor isn't an idiot, that concept should still apply to someone who is writing something decidedly (and dangerously) anti-atheist. It means more being against an idea in the category of religion, which includes atheism, even if atheism is categorized under religion solely by its lack thereof. Now, the day you start saying we should start burning Christians and Jews, and that leads to someone doing it, then we may have a problem.But that leads to the other serious problem with what this "professor" is saying. Being "anti-____" is only a crime when it's done in a way that causes severe physical or mental distress to others. Are you telling me that what this girl did caused more damage than the death threats and gunshots at her house did to her? Seriously? You can't penalize someone for simply being against something.For crying out loud, people.
