quote:How did that last entry get lumped in with all the others? Screw you, Eugene, I'm an atheist, and resent having my (non)belief associated with that list of 'views that you believe repulsive'. Sorry for the thread hijack, but someone had to call him out on this. There's a difference between being atheist or agnostic and attacking others based on their religion. It's doubtful his intent was a slight towards atheism, and more likely that his statement can be seen as a defense of your ability to defend atheism by outing the words of someone speaking derisively against it. I would suspect that his inclusion of religion was to cast a wider net in terms of a reader's ability to associate with one of the categories listed. A straight white male who doesn't steal or do drugs may otherwise have dissociated himself from this issue. Everyone has religious beliefs, whether the explicitly include or exclude a deity or acknowledge uncertainty.
wallinbl
Ars Praefectus
Registered: Dec 6, 2001Posts: 4974
Posted: Thu Apr 09, 2009 8:36 am
I would think this case could be handled via copyright. Isn't the act of posting on your MySpace an act of publishing and therefore creating copyright that is held either by the poster or MySpace or both (presumably, this depends on the MySpace TOS). If this is the case, then what right did the newspaper have to republish in an altered context? Clearly, it was not a letter to the editor, which comes with the implied intent of speaking to the readership of the paper, which is not the same as the group of people to whom she was speaking on MySpace. This would seem more appropriately published as an article or editorial about what she had said with reference to her writing and/or cited quotes.
