I have a hard time believing that taking someone's work and, without their permission, transforming it into a letter to the editor signed by that person is some sort of crime. It seems like fraud. Maybe someone more into that kind of law can enlighten us.It certainly should be against any code of journalistic ethics. The editor should at least lose her job.Now, if they wanted to get this "ode" out, the letter should have been signed by the PRINCIPAL and start with something like, "Look what I found on Facebook on a page by <the Facebook name given on that page>. . ."Since she put only her first name on the page, that is the name that should have been reported. Too bad if everyone could figure it out.
Brandon B
Ars Scholae Palatinae
Registered: Aug 4, 2003Posts: 1175
Posted: Thu Apr 09, 2009 9:27 am
While it would be actionable under copyright, that does not address the girl's issue. Her claimed damages are the reaction to, and persecution of, herself and her family. By placing the posting into a local paper which was then distributed directly to the community members, this reaction was caused. At best, demonstrating copyright infringement would get the paper a rebuke, and possibly a small damage payment, but the damage here is not financial, so it would really not be a meaningful or appropriate remedy, nor would it undo the harm in any way.However, this exact same situation could have occurred if the principal or anyone else in the town had simply come across the page and then it was distributed by chain email to all the residents (assuming they email in Coalinga), so it is pretty difficult to argue that the paper's actions are the cause. They were the means, but it likely would have occurred anyway once someone got wind of it. So basically, her own poor judgment caused the situation, and the principal's and paper's questionable actions brought it to light. If she had written glowing praise of the town and the same thing had happened, no one would even bring up copyright.
